Headline::::
When I’m 64, I’ll still be singing along




DateTime::::2016-03-08T16:59:05+0000



<p><span class="drop-cap"><span class="drop-cap__inner">T</span></span>he Beatles’ When I’m 64 has been pulled up as one of the 72% of pop and rock song lyrics that reportedly <a class="u-underline" data-component="in-body-link" data-link-name="in body link" href="http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/health-35747166" title="">portray ageing in a negative way</a>. A study by Anglia Ruskin University found that songs about ageing frequently referenced physical frailty, looming death or being unloved, unlovable or an object of pity – all of which, researchers argue, could affect the self-esteem of older people, in turn leading to more serious health problems. Strange: I was under the impression that self-esteem was only invented in around the mid-1980s.</p>

<p> <span>Related: </span><a class="u-underline" data-component="in-body-link" data-link-name="in body link" href="http://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2016/jan/03/let-everyone-age-as-gracefully-as-downton-lady-crawley">Everyone should be allowed to age as gracefully as Lady Crawley | Sonia Sodha</a> </p>

<p>While I’m aware that music has transformative qualities – it can lift, or indeed lower, your mood in a matter of minutes, I must admit that I thought the war and postwar generations were made of sterner stuff than this. When you’ve stood, aged six, peering down into a smoking crater where your neighbour’s house used to be, or suffered the indignities of a freezing outdoor toilet, are the lyrics to <a class="u-underline" data-component="in-body-link" data-link-name="in body link" href="http://www.azlyrics.com/lyrics/leonardcohen/becauseof.html" title="">Because Of by Leonard Cohen</a> really likely to give you a confidence crisis?</p>

<p>When I’m 64 is a lovely song about growing old with another person, and settling into a quieter phase of life involving knitting, gardening and grandchildren. It has its tongue firmly in its cheek, and a rousing chorus that perfectly suits kicking-out time at the local boozer. My grandparents used to sing it together joyously, and they were married for over 50 years.</p>

<p>So often it is said that ageing is a state of mind. I’m not saying growing older is a breeze, but most older people I have met seem to have no trouble keeping a sense of humour. Which is why, when I am old, I hope I’ll be the one leading the Beatles sing-along rather than the one listening to Bob Dylan’s (frankly terrible and utterly humourless) <a class="u-underline" data-component="in-body-link" data-link-name="in body link" href="http://www.azlyrics.com/lyrics/bobdylan/foreveryoung.html" title="">Forever Young</a>, which was singled out for praise.</p>

<p><a class="u-underline" data-component="in-body-link" data-link-name="in body link" href="http://www.azlyrics.com/lyrics/beatles/whenimsixtyfour.html" title="">Yours sincerely, wasting away</a>.</p>

<p>One measure that might make ageing a less painful process is the legalisation of cannabis. The latest recommendations from a panel of experts call for Britain to follow the lead of some US states and <a class="u-underline" data-component="in-body-link" data-link-name="in body link" href="http://www.theguardian.com/society/2016/mar/08/allow-cannabis-over-18s-licensed-shops-lib-dem-panel" title="">allow the sale of cannabis</a> in licensed shops (generating £1bn a year in tax revenue) and the <a class="u-underline" data-component="in-body-link" data-link-name="in body link" href="http://www.theguardian.com/society/2014/aug/15/cannabis-marijuana-medicine-law-growing" title="">home cultivation of cannabis</a> for personal use.</p>

<p>My father suffers from multiple sclerosis, the symptoms of which are greatly relieved by cannabis, so this debate is of personal interest to me, as it is to many sufferers of chronic pain. I hope June, an older lady in Cumbria who, being a keen gardener, grows it for three friends (two of whom have arthritis and one of whom has MS) aged 73, 78 and 85, is feeling cheered at the recommendations. A colleague of mine was lucky enough to meet her a couple of years back and declared her an inspiration. I wonder how many other altruistic gardeners there are out there, risking arrest in order to help their friends in need.</p>

<p><strong> </strong></p>

<p>Skiing is a way of spending time that has never appealed to me – which perhaps reveals to you my (lack of) class. I have never been anywhere near a ski slope. I’m reminded of why when looking at the <a class="u-underline" data-component="in-body-link" data-link-name="in body link" href="http://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2016/mar/07/william-and-kate-release-family-skiing-holiday-photos" title="">latest photographs</a> of the Duke and Duchess of Cambridge and their children.</p>

<p>Notwithstanding an embarrassing lack of coordination on my part, the wholesomeness of skiing – all rosy cheeks and organised fun led by girls with voluminous, side-parted hair and brisk, posh voices – frightens me a bit. For a life-endangering activity, the upper classes manage to make the whole thing look incredibly twee. But then I would say that, being more of a fag-on-a-sunlounger type than one to engage in a staged snowball fight. They say ignorance is bliss.</p>




